english:
  title: Elegy for the Party Prohibitions
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Behind closed doors I read and contemplate the ancients—
    this is what those who fail to meet their time must do.
    The old scholars said: "We mourn the past and weep for forgotten histories."
    Touched by the tales of the Party Prohibitions, I write this elegy.

    To serve the ruler with loyalty, to bestow grace upon the people—
    this is what the gentlemen aspire to.
    To harbor virtue within oneself, to move only when the moment is right—
    alas, you Party members, you stir my deepest sighs.

    Once Hong Gong and Shi Xian rose to prominence,
    they broke the Han dynasty's fate midway through its course.
    Since ancient times, when treacherous men seize power,
    few kingdoms escape their ruin.
    When slander poisons virtue itself,
    even the wise and sagacious bow their heads.

    Alas, that worthy men could not measure their own strength,
    and let loose their tongues to argue right and wrong.
    The four seas flow chaotic—who can hold back the tide with one hand?
    When a great hall totters to its fall,
    weak branches cannot bear its weight.

    The whale is mocked by ants and beetles,
    the tiny gecko scorns the soaring dragon.
    Thorns transform into orchids while the homely woman envies beauty.
    When heaven and earth exchange their places,
    fortune and misfortune push at one another.

    Xiao Wangzhi died in ancient times,
    and the Han dynasty declined.
    Chen Fan perishes now—why not depart?

    To wear darkness without is to keep brilliance within—
    this is the art of self-preservation.
    The Three Eminent and the Eight Worthies—
    who dares to acclaim them now?
    Li Ying and Du Mi share equal fame,
    yet Fan Pang's mother asked no questions.
    Huang Fu Gui's shame came
    from small cunning paired with great folly.

    Lin Zong spoke with humble grace,
    Shen Tu Pan perceived the subtle signs.
    To preserve the body and flee far away—
    this is the teaching of turbulent times.

    The orchid is consumed by its own fragrance,
    the pearl lies hidden in the depths, known to none.

    Alas, the Party members never met their moment—
    yet this too accords with Heaven's will.
  footnotes:
    - The Party Prohibitions (黨錮) refer to the political persecutions of virtuous officials during the late Eastern Han dynasty, when corrupt eunuchs and their allies targeted the scholarly class known as the Party members.
    - Hong Gong and Shi Xian were influential eunuchs whose scheming undermined Han governance.
    - 'The poem invokes various historical figures as exemplars: Xiao Wangzhi (Marquis of Lingling) and Chen Fan who resisted corruption; Li Ying and Du Mi, leaders of the Party; Fan Pang, whose mother did not doubt his virtue even in adversity; Huang Fu Gui, whose small cunning masked greater foolishness; and Lin Zong and Shen Tu Pan, who recognized danger and withdrew.'
